ough seventeen walking interviews in Hong Kong and Sydney, as potent discourses like cartographic reason continue to transform and weave through the world in ways that haunt mobile mapping and bring old conflicts into new media. In doing so, Mobile Mapping offers an interdisciplinary rethinking about how multiple translations of spatial knowledges between rational digital epistemologies and tacit ways of understanding space and experience might be conceptualized and researched.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCell phonesxSocial aspects. 0aCommunication. Mass media. 0aDigital mappingxSocial aspects. 0aDigital mapsxSocial aspects. 0aInformation technology. 0aLaw in general. Comparative and uniform law. Jurisprudence. 0aSociology (General). 4aContemporary Society. 4aDigital and Social Media. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 4aPolitics and Government. 7aCOMPUTERS / Digital Media / General.2bisacsh  aDigital media, mobile mapping, mobile method, urban spaces, ethnographies of everyday life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060672008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048535217zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048535217zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048535217.jpg  a978-3-11-060672-0 Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-069629-5 DG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA